Lesson 19: Higher-Order Components (HOCs)
What are Higher-Order Components?
A Higher-Order Component (HOC) is a function that takes a component as an argument and returns a new component. Itâ€™s a pattern used for reusing component logic.

Use Case
HOCs are commonly used for:

Adding authentication checks
Logging
Fetching data
Managing permissions
Example: A Simple HOC
jsx
Copy code
import React from "react";

// Higher-Order Component
function withGreeting(WrappedComponent) {
  return function EnhancedComponent(props) {
    return (
      <div>
        <h1>Hello, User!</h1>
        <WrappedComponent {...props} />
      </div>
    );
  };
}

// Base Component
function Dashboard() {
  return <p>Welcome to the dashboard!</p>;
}

// Enhanced Component
const EnhancedDashboard = withGreeting(Dashboard);

export default EnhancedDashboard;
Lesson 20: React Portals
What are React Portals?
React Portals allow you to render a child component into a DOM node outside of the parent componentâ€™s DOM hierarchy.

Use Case
Modals
Tooltips
Notifications
Example: Using React Portals
jsx
Copy code
import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom";

function Modal({ isOpen, children }) {
  if (!isOpen) return null;

  return ReactDOM.createPortal(
    <div style={{ background: "rgba(0,0,0,0.5)", padding: "20px" }}>
      {children}
    </div>,
    document.getElementById("modal-root") // Target DOM node
  );
}

function App() {
  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = React.useState(false);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => setIsOpen(true)}>Open Modal</button>
      <Modal isOpen={isOpen}>
        <h1>Modal Content</h1>
        <button onClick={() => setIsOpen(false)}>Close Modal</button>
      </Modal>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
Lesson 21: Controlled vs. Uncontrolled Components
Controlled Components
The React component controls the form inputs' state.

Example

jsx
Copy code
function ControlledForm() {
  const [name, setName] = React.useState("");

  return (
    <form>
      <input
        type="text"
        value={name}
        onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
      />
      <p>Your Name: {name}</p>
    </form>
  );
}
Uncontrolled Components
The DOM manages the state of the form inputs.

Example

jsx
Copy code
function UncontrolledForm() {
  const inputRef = React.useRef();

  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    console.log("Name:", inputRef.current.value);
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input type="text" ref={inputRef} />
      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  );
}
